  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's a lived reality for many individuals, especially those from underrepresented groups. As a translator who's worked with academic texts, I've seen how language barriers and unconscious biases can amplify this issue. For instance, when students from minority backgrounds are reminded of stereotypes about their group's intellectual capabilities before a test, their performance often drops because their minds are preoccupied with the fear of confirming the stereotype rather than focusing on the task. This phenomenon isn't about individual failure; it's about systemic pressures that make certain groups feel like they don't belong in STEM fields. Given my own background as someone raised in a family where formal education wasn't always prioritized—my father had no formal education and my mother only completed upper secondary school—I understand the weight of expectations and the emotional toll of being perceived as 'less capable.' That's why I believe we must address stereotype threat head-on. We need to create inclusive environments where everyone feels safe to explore STEM without fear of judgment. This means integrating storytelling into STEM education, sharing diverse role models, and fostering mentorship programs that highlight success stories from all backgrounds. It's not just about changing policies—it's about changing the culture. As someone who values creativity and empathy, I see that when students feel seen and supported, their potential blossoms. In Bari, where I live, there are already grassroots initiatives that encourage local youth to engage with science through art and hands-on projects. These efforts remind me that the solution isn't abstract—it's rooted in community and understanding. Addressing stereotype threat requires intentional, compassionate action, not just awareness. It's time to build a STEM ecosystem where everyone has the opportunity to thrive.",
